# Updating Context Files

This directory contains the **Context Updater** workflow, the optional update agent, and update metadata. Use it to keep your `.ai/context/` files in sync as your project evolves — without re-running the full bootstrap process.

You can use this module from:

- GitHub Copilot, by temporarily copying in the update agent
- another coding assistant, by following `UPDATE.md`
- a manual review flow, by reading the update docs and running the helper scripts yourself

## When to Update

Run an update when:
- Database schema has changed (new tables, columns, migrations)
- New API endpoints have been added or removed
- Roles or permissions have been modified
- Framework or dependency versions have been upgraded
- The context files look stale

## How to Run

### Tool-Neutral Path

Open `.ai/update/UPDATE.md` in your coding assistant and start with:

```text
Use .ai/update/README.md and .ai/update/UPDATE.md to refresh the generated context files. Re-scan the repository, show me the drift, and only apply approved updates.
```

### GitHub Copilot Path

1. Copy the update agent into your agents directory

```bash
cp .ai/update/update.agent.md .github/agents/context-updater.agent.md
```

Reload VS Code:

> **Cmd+Shift+P** → `Developer: Reload Window`

2. Run the Context Updater

1. Open **Copilot Chat**
2. Select **Claude Sonnet 4.6** (or Opus 4.6 for large projects)
3. Select **Context Updater** from the chat mode dropdown
4. Send: **"Update context files"**

The agent will:
- Scan the codebase for changes since the last update
- Present a detailed change report (new tables, endpoints, roles, etc.)
- Ask for your approval before modifying any files
- Update data files (`.jsonl`, `.yaml`) directly
- Suggest changes to prose files (`.md`) for your review
- Detect version drift in `toolkit.config.yaml`

### Review and commit

```bash
git add .ai/
git commit -m "chore: update AI context files"
git push origin your-branch
```

### Clean up (optional)

If you copied the update agent into `.github/agents/`, remove it when you're done:

```bash
rm .github/agents/context-updater.agent.md
```

The underlying update workflow remains here in `.ai/update/` for the next run.

## Update Metadata

After each update, the agent writes `.ai/update/.last-updated` with:
- Timestamp of the last update
- Which files were updated
- Summary of changes detected

This helps the agent know what changed between updates.

## Update Strategy

| File Type | Strategy | Safe? |
|-----------|----------|-------|
| `.jsonl` data files | Full regenerate (add new, remove stale) | Yes — structured data |
| `.yaml` data files | Full regenerate (merge new) | Yes — structured data |
| `.md` prose files | **Suggest only** — user reviews diff | Yes — never auto-overwrites |

